  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial Offering for the Venerable Master Chung-gyeong
  author: Seok Bok'am
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The mirror of wisdom gleams with radiance,
    Revealing both barbarian and Han in a single moment.
    Yet the lamp of the world grows dim,
    And heaven and earth darken in one brief dawn.

    So we turn to the gate of compassion,
    And solemnly cultivate our repayment.
    Our Master appeared in this world,
    Riding the original vow to spread the way of meditation.
    His teaching blessed all beings—
    Once the standard of the Three Lands,
    His virtue filled both court and commons,
    Until he became the teacher of two sovereigns.

    The nation's fortune and welfare—
    All eyes gaze upon it.
    The way of the ancestors—
    One body upheld its rise and fall.
    Why then such haste to depart this world,
    Such urgency to leave?

    The temple forests grow desolate—where shall we lean?
    The cosmos turns empty—where shall we dwell?
    We collapse in grief upon the ground,
    Like children torn from their mother's breast.
    We wander lost and pitiful,
    Like a dog without a home.

    Yet seeing his lifetime of practice,
    He surely plays at leisure in his original nature.
    Still, we hold this offering—
    Merely honoring human affection.

    As the forty-nine days arrive,
    We present the Three Treasures.
    Each lamp transforms into towers of light,
    Shining throughout the dharma realm.
    Each grain of rice becomes celestial fragrance,
    Filling the emptiness of true nature.

    This humble heart shines clear—
    Please illuminate it.

    Humbly we pray:
    May he ascend directly to the path of enlightenment,
    Walking together with all the accomplished ones.
    May he return to the gate of the ancestors,
    And leave not a single being untransformed.
  footnotes:
    - The 'mirror of wisdom' is a metaphor for the Buddha-nature that reveals truth universally, transcending cultural boundaries ('barbarian and Han').
    - The 'lamp of the world' refers to the teacher's physical presence; its dimming represents his death.
    - The 'Three Lands' (三韓) is a traditional name for Korea.
    - '''The original vow'' refers to the bodhisattva vow taken in past lives.'
    - The 'forty-nine days' (七七齋) is the traditional Korean Buddhist mourning period, consisting of seven weeks of memorial services.
    - The final prayer echoes the bodhisattva vow to save all beings, suggesting the deceased master will continue his work in the spiritual realm.
